<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1940-12-18T12:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1940-12-18T12:00:00-05:00" n="571" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d571">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">761.74/62: Telegram</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Bulgaria</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Earle</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to
                                the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                            </hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sofia</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1940-12-18T19:00:00+02:00">December
                                    18, 1940—7 p.m.</date>
                                <lb/> [Received 7:15 p.m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>189. Ganovsky, Secretary of the Bulgarian Communist organization
                            (illegal) informs me that Soboleff asked the King for naval and air
                            bases in Bulgaria. Russia in return offered to force Turkey to give
                            Adrianople and Turkish Thrace to Bulgaria and to exert all possible
                            pressure on Greece to cede Grecian Thrace to the Kavala–Drama line.</p>
                        <p>Ganovsky says that the King has courteously but firmly refused Russia’s
                            proposals.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Earle</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>